textDisplay: He doesnt really have a business case here because he doesnt own his ip. All he has here is a customer base, a very small one at that if were talking the beverage industry. His prob is hes just mixing tampico and hennessy, neither of which he owns and is easy for anyone to replicate. Hennessy has 0 reason to work with him, if they like it they can cut him out n just partner with tampico or their own juice. I like this dude, I just dont think he knows much about intellectual property. If he wants to have a business thats scalable he needs to create his own unique recipe, and then either do some small scale distilling or partner with a craft distillery, and distributer. That way he owns the ip of a unique recipe thats his own that cant be easily replicated (thats why coke is so huge), and he needs to have the actual distillery and fruit/ingredient vendors hes partnering with. He needs to own the recipe and ingredients and then its something scalable. Until then its just henny n juice. I like his hustle I hope he invests in himself and does this. Oh yea on top of that he needs to register a business name, prob llc, and pay taxes. Then he can hope to scale up to put his drink in stores one day. Until then no big name company is gonna touch this with a ten foot pole.
